{{Infobox person |name = Paul Isenberg |image = Paul Isenberg (1837-1903).jpg |image_size = |caption = Newspaper sketch from 1904 |birth_date = {{Birth date|1837|4|15}} |birth_place = [[Dransfeld]], [[Germany]] |death_date = {{Death date and age|1903|1|16|1837|4|15}} |death_place = [[Bremen]], [[Germany]] |children = |parents = |spouse = Maria Rice |occupation = Businessman |known_for = [[Amfac, Inc.]] }}
'''Paul Isenberg''' (April 15, 1837 – January 16, 1903) was a [[German people|German]] businessman who developed the [[sugarcane]] business in the [[Kingdom of Hawaii]].
==Life== Paul Heinrich Friedrich Carl Isenberg was born April 15, 1837 in [[Dransfeld]], [[Kingdom of Hanover]], [[Germany]].<ref name="papers">{{cite web |title= Finding Aid for Isenberg Collection |work= Kaua’i Historical Society |year= 2010 |author=Marylou Bradley and Carolyn Dettling |url= http://www.kauaihistoricalsociety.org/assets/finding_aids/ms_57_isenberg_collection.pdf |accessdate= September 23, 2010 }}</ref> His father was [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] minister Daniel Isenberg (1807–1875), and mother was Dorothea (Strauch) Isenberg (1808–1871). He came to the [[Hawaiian Islands]] in 1858, and became known as Paul Isenberg.
Isenberg moved to the island of [[Kauai|Kaua{{okina}}i]] and first worked in [[Wailua, Kauai|Wailua]]. In October 1861 he married Hannah "Maria" Rice, daughter of [[William Harrison Rice]], who was born February 17, 1842, and died April 7, 1867. They had two children, Mary Dorothea Rice Isenberg (1862–1949) and Daniel Paul Rice Isenberg (1866–1919) known as "Paul Jr." He traveled back to Germany in 1869 where he married Beta Margarete Glade (born 1846) before returning to Hawaii. They had six more children: Johannes "John" Carl Isenberg (born September 12, 1870), Heinrich Alexander Isenberg (born January 17, 1872), Julie Maria Pauline (Isenberg) Barckhausen (born November 1876), Clara Margarete (Isenberg) Wendroth (born 1878), Richard Menno Isenberg (born 1880) and Paula Bertha Johanna Isenberg (born 1883).<ref name="adv"/>
Isenberg took over managing the [[sugarcane]] [[Sugar plantations in Hawaii|plantation]] at [[Lihue, Hawaii|Līhuʻe]] in 1862, after the death of his father-in-law who was previous manager. The plantation was founded by diplomat [[Henry A. Peirce]], but struggled to make a profit until Rice built an irrigation system. Isenberg made improvements to the [[cane sugar mill]] such as using an evaporating pan and steam pipes to concentrate the cane juice. In 1872 the Lihue Plantation company was officially incorporated, and the {{convert |3300|acre}} expanded by {{convert |17000|acre}} at [[Hanamaulu, Hawaii|Hanamāʻulu]].<ref name="lihue">{{cite web |title= Finding Aid for Lihue Plantation Collection |work= Kaua’i Historical Society |year= 2009 |author= Marylou Bradley |url= http://www.kauaihistoricalsociety.org/assets/finding_aids/ms45_lihue_plantation_finding_aid.pdf |accessdate= September 24, 2010 |deadurl= yes |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110726213834/http://www.kauaihistoricalsociety.org/assets/finding_aids/ms45_lihue_plantation_finding_aid.pdf |archivedate= July 26, 2011 |df= }}</ref> On January 24, 1874 he was appointed to the upper House of Nobles in the [[legislature of the Hawaiian Kingdom]] by King [[Lunalilo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archives1.dags.hawaii.gov/gsdl/collect/governme/index/assoc/HASH5b09/3945a7b2.dir/Isenberg,%20Paul%20Daniel%20Rice%20I.jpg |title= Isenberg, Daniel Paul Rice I office record |work=state archives digital collections |publisher=state of Hawaii |accessdate= September 24, 2010 }} Note name not accurate</ref> He officially became a citizen of the [[Kingdom of Hawaii]] at that time.<ref>{{Hawaiian Dictionaries |Citizenship - Naturalization: page 51 Ieatmann - Ives |D29-000052 |q=Isenberg |dic=gene |accessdate= September 24, 2010}}</ref> In 1877 he bought equipment for a new mill from [[George Norton Wilcox]] and installed it at Hanamāʻulu to be managed by [[Albert Spencer Wilcox]].<ref name="lihue"/>
In 1878 Isenberg retired as plantation manager, but kept an ownership interest while moving his family back to [[Bremen]] in Germany. He visited the islands at least every two years for legislative sessions. His brother Carl Isenberg then managed the plantation. In 1881 Isenberg became a business partner with earlier German merchant Heinrich Hackfeld in his Hackfeld & Company.<ref name="adv">{{cite book |title= The Story of Hawaii and Its Builders |year=1925 |publisher= [[Honolulu Star Bulletin]] |editor= George F. Nellist |url= http://files.usgwarchives.net/hi/statewide/bios/isenberg34bs.txt |chapter= Isenberg, Paul }}</ref> Although most other plantation laborers were Chinese or Japanese, Isenberg arranged for groups of workers from Bremen to settle on his company's plantations.<ref name="kingdom3">{{cite book |title=Hawaiian Kingdom 1874-1893, the Kalakaua Dynasty |author= [[Ralph Simpson Kuykendall]] |url= http://www.ulukau.org/elib/cgi-bin/library?c=kingdom3&l=en |volume=3 |publisher= University of Hawaii Press |year= 1967 |isbn= 978-0-87022-433-1 |page=}}</ref>{{rp|134–135}} In the 1887 session of the legislature, he was one of the few who objected to the threat of military force that caused the [[1887 Constitution of the Kingdom of Hawaii]] to be called the "Bayonet Constitution".<ref name="kingdom3"/>{{rp|361–362}}
He died in Bremen on January 16, 1903.<ref>{{cite news |title= Paul Isenberg Dies at Bremen, in the 66th Year of his Age |newspaper= Hawaiian Gazette |location= Honolulu |date= January 20, 1903 |url= http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83025121/1903-01-20/ed-1/seq-6/ |accessdate= September 24, 2010 }}</ref>
==Legacy== {{Big Five Hawaii}} Hackfeld & Company grew to be one of the "[[Big Five (Hawaii)|Big Five]]" corporations that dominated the economy of the [[Territory of Hawaii]]. During [[World War I]], Hackfeld & Company was seized by the U.S. government [[Alien Property Custodian]] along with other assets owned by Germans. It was sold to a consortium of Hawaii businessmen in 1918, who changed the name to "American Factors" and the company's store [[Liberty House (US)|Liberty House]]. A 1920 lawsuit argued the price was below market value, and some former stockholders including John Carl Isenberg recovered some damages.<ref>{{cite journal |hdl= 10524/462 |title= German Sugar's Sticky Fingers |journal= Hawaiian Journal of History |publisher=Hawaiian Historical Society |volume= 16 |author= Frederick Bernays Wiener |year= 1982 |pages= 15–47}}</ref> In 1966, the name was further shortened to [[Amfac, Inc.]]
His son Paul Jr. married Annie Beatrice McBryde, daughter of neighboring sugar planter Duncan McBryde on October 19, 1891.<ref>{{Hawaiian Dictionaries |Oahu (1832-1910) marriage record |D09-000108 |q=Isenberg |dic=gene |accessdate= September 24, 2010}}</ref> On August 31, 1891 [[Liliuokalani|Queen Lili{{okina}}uokalani]] appointed him to the [[Privy Council]]. From 1898 to 1915 he was elected as representative to the house of representatives of the [[Territory of Hawaii]], and from 1902 to 1905 the senate.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://archives1.dags.hawaii.gov/gsdl/collect/governme/index/assoc/HASHc539/62b67ce7.dir/Isenberg,%20Daniel%20Paul%20Rice%20II.jpg |title= Isenberg, Daniel Paul Rice (II) office record |work=state archives digital collections |publisher=state of Hawaii |accessdate= September 24, 2010 }}</ref> He married Bertha Koepke on August 9, 1916, and they had one child, Dorothea "Dora" Jane Isenberg (1917–1988), who married Joseph Cole.<ref>{{cite book |title= The Story of Hawaii and Its Builders |year=1925 |publisher= [[Honolulu Star Bulletin]] |editor= George F. Nellist |url= http://files.usgwarchives.net/hi/statewide/bios/isenberg33bs.txt |chapter= Isenberg, Daniel Paul Rice }}</ref> Cole was first manager of the [[Kauai Museum|Kaua{{okina}}i Museum]] in 1960.<ref>{{cite web |title= Kauaʻi Museum |work= official web site |url= http://www.kauaimuseum.org/ |accessdate= October 1, 2010 }}</ref> In 1887 his younger brother Johannes Friedrich Wilhelm "Hans" Isenberg (1855–1918) was brought in to be pastor of the first Lutheran church on the island for the immigrants who starting arriving in 1881.<ref>{{cite web |title= Our History & Heritage |work= official web page |publisher= Lihue Lutheran Church |url= http://www.lihuelutheran.com/ |accessdate= September 24, 2010}}</ref> Hans had married his own niece, Paul's first child, Mary Dorothea Rice Isenberg, known as Dora, in 1883.<ref name="papers"/>
